inn1.comm: half-paced loosener just outside off stump, carefully pushed into the off side
outside off stump, gentle swing but after the ball had passed the batsman
same line, again a little swing and a bit more bounce, and Vincent is content to leave the ball well alone

what a start!  full length on off stump, Vincent doesn't get fully forward and the ball, which swung a little away from him, finds the outside edge and is well caught at waist height at second slip by a delighted Steve Tikolo
good ball first up, through Taylor who is on a pair in this tournament
Odoyo again finds the edge, this time the ball goes all along the ground through the vacant third-slip area
outside the off stump, Taylor cautiously watches it pass
Taylor forward, a controlled outside edge dribbles all along the ground to third man
Fleming forward to meet the ball with the full face
Fleming a bit more rushed, half forward to push the ball to point
swung across the left hander at 74mph, Fleming having none of it

a pearl of a ball which is through Fleming, on edge, which is just as well as Ouma dropped it. Abeed Janmohamed, who is Kenya's No. 2 keeper and who is sitting nearby, lets out a loud roar of disapproval
gentle swing away from Taylor, no shot
Taylor probes and is beaten. No real pace - 74mph - but his line is good and the gentle awayswing is causing problems
Taylor half steers, half edges the ball to third man
on middle-and-off, solid defence from Fleming
Fleming pushes rather tentatively into the covers
crashed drive through point, a classy shot to get off the mark, the first bad ball from Odoyo, too much width
well forward and blocked
driven past a diving extra cover, not timed so it never has the legs to get all the way to the rope
Ongondo overstretches and Taylor drives, again not at all timed and extra cover fields
full, a crisp on drive and mid-on across to his left smartly to prevent the run

flicked uppishly to square leg, a loose shot, Tanmay Mishra dives to his right and in the end goes for the one-handed catch which he spills. It was hard but he did the hard work to get there in the first place
pushed to extra cover
a firm drive to extra cover, much harder, but well stopped
Fleming well forward to defend
Odoyo drifts to leg, flicked away to backward square where the man in the deep fields
Taylor forward, blocks, and holds the pose for any passing photographers
Odoyo goes wide in the crease to change the angle of attack, Taylor into line and defends rather off balance on the walk
again Taylor ends up square on as he defends, pushing the ball to mid-on
Odoyo, gold chain bouncing up and down as he bowls, fires it in outside off stump and Taylor rather sniffily watches it pass
good line and length, Fleming, taking no risks at this stage, defends
defensive shot, but this time with an angled bat and the batsmen amble a single to the right of point
leg side, turned, again a bit uppishly but this time quite safely, to the deep where long leg has too much ground to make up and cannot prevent a second
checked drive-push and the ball arcs back towards mid-on, never a catch though
Taylor's preferred shot of late, worked off middle-and-leg with a roll of the wrists behind square on the leg side
a bit of a slash but banged right into the ground and the ball bounces gently to point
lovely shot, on leg stump and Fleming drives it to the left of mid-on who is reduced to the role of spectator. Fleming is so strong off his pads ...
Fleming back and plays a slightly ugly block-push off the back foot to mid-off
solidly forward and pushed to extra cover
back and played easily to mid-off
Odoyo strays to leg again and Fleming whips that fine, Hiren Varaiya makes a good sprawling stop to cheers from both of the fans
pushed to extra cover, Fleming takes a couple of strides but barring a crass misfield, there was never a run there
right through Taylor's jerky jab. The batsman pulled his bat away as if to show he had left it, but we weren't fooled
slashed down to wide third man
Fleming back on his toes to block
pushed back to Ongondo
dropped into the off side, no more than seven or eight feet, and a well-run single
checked drive to extra cover
short and Fleming pounces, lifting that high into the stands beyond the midwicket boundary. Great timing. That was the shot that led to his downfall against England
pushed into the off side, extra cover in quickly
a grunt from Odoyo as he spears one across Fleming who goes forward and then leaves
Fleming shapes to work the ball to leg, misses, and is struck high on the pad. No appeal, but a stifled grunt from the bowler
flicked to leg, a thick inside edge onto his pad, and Ouma hurries out to field
Taylor well forward
short and Fleming helps that on his way - no real backlift - and it just about clears the backward square leg boundary. He looked slightly uneasy as that was in the air but it had enough
pressed into the off side
turned square as he shaped to block, a thick edge goes along the ground to third man
seamed into the right-hander, into the leg side for a quick run, but Mishra then shies at the bowler's end and nobody is backing up, so producing an overthrow
Taylor leaves it alone outside the off stump
driven to mid-off but he is struggling to find the gaps
that one's worked into the covers and there's an easy single
in a good area, coming into the righthander, and that's defended on the front foot
pitched outside off, a touch short, and the batsman plays a high-batted off drive that's picked up by the mid-off easily
outside off again and that ball's worked forward once more
poked into the covers this time
creeps over that one and tickles it to the man in at short midwicket
defended first up
ooh, well worth a shout - and it duly comes - but that was over the stumps
this one nearly through Fleming, who's saved only by an edge into his pads
Fleming shapes to drive forward and doesn't quite get hold of the ball
"Howzat?" they cry as Fleming loses his balance coming forward to try to work that into the leg side
down leg and Fleming tries to work that to leg but doesn't get hold of it
worked away to the deep square leg boundary
Fleming goes for the pull shot, trying to go very square of the wicket but he misses and that hits him at a painful height
creeps over the ball to defend that one into the covers

...although that was a jolly nice shot from a loose delivery - a lovely pull with consummate timing, Fleming coming towards the ball and sending that high into the stands and that brings up New Zealand's fifty
short, on leg, and that's tricked into the leg side
outside off and that's worked forward to mid-off
flashes at that one - gamely chasing after a widesish one, which was also an overstep
driven on the front foot straight to cover
on off and dabbed down off the back foot in front of him
prodded outside off and that was taken by the keeper
a touch of width and that's worked out to point
off the back foot and that's worked straight to one of the fielders in the inner ring
comes forward and walks into that one and that's played to mid-on
short and way outside off and that's clunked off the back foot through wide third man
short, wide outside the off stump and that's smashed through point for four, Fleming quickly on to that one, eyes wide and alert
dibbled into the covers
driven to mid-on without much power or, indeed, timing
on off and that was pushed down the ground with some decent timing this time and that fair races away through mid-on. No need to run f...
slightly slower ball, good length on the toes and that's defended forward

up there, dabbed down off the back foot, short, and there's some shuffling through from the batsmen - a hesitation from Taylor in his running but would have been safe even if there had been a direct hit at the non-striker's end
short and bunted in front of midwicket, a lot of bottom hand, and played with quite short arms - ie not much room - and that's wristed away very quickly and cleanly indeed. Great timing
on a good length and that's defended forward
taken from outside off, short, and whisked right in front of midwicket again
driven easily into the covers
down the off channel and Taylor plays over that one, mistiming it and in fact missing it
too much width on off and that's lamped - not with a lamp, but with a bat - off the back foot, low, with a lovely, thumping cut
on off and Fleming thinks about working that one into the leg side but stops on the shot
oversteps and that's jinked off the pads behind the keeper
short and a touch wide outside off, and that's whipped into the covers but misses out as it goes straight to the fielder
taken off the pads and worked in front of midwicket
straight and defended down off the back foot
tickled into the covers
taken off the front foot and worked high in front of the man inside the midwicket boundary, well timed
on a good length on off and that's worked into the covers on the front foot
short on off and the rising ball is played down off the toes behind point
gets away with a streaky edge, there, thick outside number flying way past the keeper and on its way. Fleming didn't even blink, never mind step out of his crease to set off for the run
straight, and moving away a touch from the lefthander who plays it down on the front foot
straight again and driven sumptuously down the ground to bring up Fleming's fifty, he's looking well in his groove now and that's ominous for Kenya
slower ball, picked up easily, and Fleming caresses that one off the front foot through cover
wristed - a la Pietersen - into the short midwicket, Taylor rolling his wrists over that one to take the ball from off to leg
worked into leg again, no power
wide down leg this time
comes forward to drive that one to mid-on and that brings up New Zealand's hundred
oh, tricky ball that, pitching off and bending away from the lefthander, who plays a false stroke to that
defended on the front foot this time
on off and that's driven to mid-on this time
some turn first up, slow, and Taylor had to wait a while for this before defending
full toss swept to the man inside the midwicket boundary
comes forward to defend
comes forward, again, and the bowler adjusts, putting that in front of the off stick and defended forward
worked into the on side off the front foot
like Nigel Mansell in his heyday - see I told you I was in the 80s - the batsman finds the gap while driving (through cover)

crazy run and an appalling error of judgment. Taylor flicked the ball to backward square, right to him, Fleming called and all Obuya, Kenya's best fielder, had to do was pick and throw accurately, which he did, and Fleming was so far short that it didn't even need the third umpire
turned to square leg
worked from off stump into space the leg side
forward, everything into line and no run
swished square on the leg side, Obuya trots round to field
leg-side half-volley, paddled round the corner, it bounced a yard in front of Obuya and through his dive
gently pushed to mid-on
clipped off his toes but Mishra at midwicket dives to his left and makes a really good stop
short, cut through cover. Ongondo dived and had it covered but the ball spun on bouncing and that took ti wide of his grasp
good line, blocked
turned into the on side, long leg has a long way to come back and Taylor just beats his accurate throw. An unnecessary risk at this stage
flighted on off stump, Taylor plays an uncertain checked drive into the off
Styris back, waits, and drives to long-on
driven to long-on. A run a ball with that shot
same shot, same end result. Tikolo won't be happy to allow this to go on unchecked
Taylor waits and then flicks the ball square on the leg side
Styris forward to one thrown up and it spins into the batsman
driven to ... yes, you guessed it, long-on
pushed off the back foot into the off
defensive prod, nothing dramatic
Styris uses his feet to meet a ball drifting into his legs and thumps it back over the bowler's head for six. Great use of the feet ...
flicked to leg, Mishra in quickly to field
pushed up to long-on, all along the ground
patted to mid-off
whipped right to Mishra at midwicket
Styris waits and steers that to the left of Mishra
worked to the right of the busy Mishra, who scurries to retrieve
pushed back to the right of the bowler, who gets across to field
and once again Kamande fields off his bowling
cut, but with no power, and point has no difficulty in gathering it
turned to Mishra at midwicket  .. the ball is following him wherever he goes
exaggerated forward defensive, head right over the ball
driven on the walk to mid-on
straight drive on the off side, again into a large gap left there
Taylor takes a stride to meet the ball and whips it up the ground to long-on
upright and technically sound drive to long-on ... no real power but then again it didn't have to be hit
slightly short, punched to long-off
pushed back to the bowler
flicked to midwicket where Mishra is quickly in
hit across the line, MIshra there again
Taylor waits, paddles round the corner where Obuya pounces
Taylor works into the leg side and sets off quickly for the single to bring up his 3rd ODI fifty
flicked to Obuya who is on the one round the corner on the leg side
at this pace the batsmen can wait and push into space ... as Taylor did there
leg-side wide, Ouma half stops
dropped flighted half volley deceives Styris and Kamande spills a sitter at midwicket. he juggled the ball three times before spilling it
nurdled into space on the off
firm drive to extra cover
wristy flick to square leg
wide half volley, Taylor unleashes a spanking cover drive which races across the outfield. Nobody moves
spun across Taylor - it turned appreciably - but Ouma nowhere near it and it races unhindered to the rope
good recovery, worked gently to midwicket
Taylor waits and paddles into space on the leg side
full, and at this pace the batsmen can wait and pick their spot. This time it was square on the leg side
same old story ... into one of the wide gaps on leg
driven to long-on, Kamande tried to get across to field but he was never in the picture
pushed to midwicket
same ball again ends up in the hands of midwicket
patted to deep square leg
mistimed flip round the corner, it dribbles to Obuya
terrible ball, so wide down the leg side that it was always wide and Ouma so slow to get across that it's another four wides
another wide. No excuses for Tikolo. He's hardly a novice and his side are looking to him to lead them out of this bad spell
another wide. No excuses for Tikolo. He's hardly a novice and his side are looking to him to lead them out of this bad spell
dead batted and a good run
finds the gap through midwicket - didn't middle it but the placement was enough and there's a lunge that can only be described as 'despairing' on the boundary
nibbled into the off side
on leg and tracked out to square with a firm bunt
outside off, the batsman creeps right over and into that shot, a firm cover drive and there's some quick running
wide outside off and that's cut down off the back foot to Varaiya inside the boundary - Kamande not settling with his line here
drops that one short and the batsman picks off another single, working that one to square
drags that short, outside off, and it's cut away to point where there's another mis-field, the wheels have come off Kenya's fielding here

half a chance with a run out, there, and Mishra, the thrower, thinks he's got his man Taylor. Tikolo collects the wide throw and moves it onto the stumps - but the batsman's well home and the third umpire doesn't need too many replays to confirm
worked into midwicket and that's picked up easily by the fielder
driven to midwicket
worked off the toes to midwicket once more and "Kamande, Kamande, Kamande" Tikolo command-es of the fielder
very wide down leg, nothing short of useless, and a puff-cheeked Tikolo gets a stern word from the skipper - ie talks to himself, but you knew that
played forward for a quick strike-stealing single
goes down leg, that's well driven out to long-on where David Obuya does some tidy work and gives a big, satisfied grin as a result
round the wicket, on off, and that's very well worked out to long-on
driven out to long-off
driven straight to the fielder at mid-off
outside off and jinked to midwicket with a down-on-one-knee sweep
outside off, dragged down a touch, and that's eased off the back foot to just inside the cover boundary
defended forward
top-edge sweep clogged out of the ground, stepping into that one and that's a big blow
tried again and just got a prospective bruise for his troubles, clattering that into his thigh
he's gone this time - a soft pop back up to the bowler, snapped low, who doesn't even celebrate
worked to midwicket
driven to mid-off
pushed up there but the batsman does well to work that one to cover
steps into that one and drives on the up straight to the fielder
a lovely straight bat again and another single is oozed out to mid-off
on the money and that's defended forward
driven to the covers
wide down leg, although perhaps a tad harsh
stands tall and drives that one to the covers
Ouma missed that chance down the leg side, a mere flick away fine
driven in front of midwicket
good ball, up there and there's a hint of turn into the righthander
short, wide, rubbish, but McMillan makes no mistake, rocking back, making room and slashing that hard behind point
steps into that one, but the length is better than he thought and has to adjust to stopping on the shot
played in front of square
worked into midwicket
driven lazily out to mid off
clubbed away firmly off the back foot just inside the cover boundary and there's just a single
driven to long off this time
"Catch it" comes the hopeful cry as that's dinked up in front of square
Styris shuffles about and finally comes forward into that one, working off his legs to mid-on
swept round behind square for a cheeky single
a huge six - right onto the roof over mid-on, danced into that one and that's gone a long, long way
defended off the back foot
short and played into the leg side, popping up a touch but into space
played into square leg
on leg and that's played into leg again
worked off the toes in front of leg again
on middle and that's worked into the leg side
on leg stump and that's worked in front of midwicket
worked to short midwicket
driven off the legs into the on side
driven into the off side
on leg and that's worked into the leg side
on off, short, rising a touch and that's worked back down off the back foot
short, a touch of width outside off and that's worked towards the midwicket boundary where Shah fields well with a knee-sliding dive-and-scoop affair
"How was that? How was he?" demands Ouma, thinking he's taken a fine outside edge, but in fact he hasn't - there was no contact, according to Umpire Doctrove
on middle and that comes off the toe of the bat into space
huge outside edge flies high over to the vacant third man slot - he'd actually meant to send that in front of midwicket
finds midwicket this time
on off and that's clubbed away into the grandstand which sits behind mid on (or third man, depending on which end they're bowling from... and yes, this only applies to the righthander, too)
tucked into the leg side this time
huge thwack, a one-handed blow, great shot coming down the wicket
tries to work that off the legs and it crashes into his pads, but going down leg and there's no hint of an appeal
down on one knee and that's lashed from outside off to very fine long-on
driven out to long-on this time
worked out to long-on and despite the urgent chirping in the middle, the fielder can't save the single, and he throws it back in gently
on middle, pushed right up there and that's well bowled, the batsman driving out to mid off
driven straight to long-on, hit much firmer, and that brings up Styris's fifty. He pauses only briefly for the applause and the cameras, before gum-chewing his way back to his mark
dropped. Styris nearly falls immediately after the milestone, belting that without connecting fully, to the man at short midwicket who makes a valiant one-handed attempt
lashed over midwicket this time - six all the way onto the scoresheet
driven off the toes to mid-on this time and that's another expensive over
... not on that evidence. Short and sent high over deep square leg, easily clearing the man on the rope
better from Odoyo, driven forward without much power
yorker, pretty slow, well dug out - and that was an over-stepped no-ball
slower delivery, aiming at leg, and that's picked off into the covers off the back foot
short, outside off, and Styris swings that through the leg side again, this time through midwicket
slower ball, dragged down, and there's more swinging, but Styris doesn't time that one too well
outside off and smashed to extra cover where Tikolo makes a decent captain's stop, setting a good example

Mishra takes a good catch at long-on, a safe take in the end, keeping his eyes on it all the way. Lots of height on that skyer, but not much distance sadly for the batsman, who walks off still chewing gum
worked off the toes in front of midwicket and Oram's now on strike, and ready to roll
on leg and that's eased away off the toes with a flick through midwicket
wobbles a bit in the air, there, and angles in on leg stump, the batsman wafting it into the leg side
right up there, better length, and that's dug out
another tidy yorker and that was dug out well once more
driven out through extra cover, I think he was trying to drive that straighter, but nevermind, they're all runs and they all count
effortlessly eased with a late dink off the back foot to third man, lovely quick hands and that's an attractive shot
dinked down to gully and there's a big, barked "No!" lest there be any confusion about going for a single

short and straight ball, slower too, and there's a swing and a miss to bring up Odoyo's 100th one-day wicket. That was well bowled, hitting the top of the sticks, and a timely wicket for Kenya who will now hope that will contribute towards some damage limitation at the death
defends into the leg side first up, thinking about driving that, but pulling out of the shot
defended forward
driven out to long-off
another off-side drive, this one creamed out to extra cover
a low full toss on leg and that's helped on its way for four in front of midwicket - well placed, not trying to play that one too hard
driven to midwicket
yorker, and that's well dug out
well timed over midwicket, what looks like a mere flick travels far and high, lovely
defended this time
driven straight
left alone outside off

ah, the heavy bails prevent a wicket - as that would have gone on to take the lighter bails off, the ball crunching into the stumps as the batsman plays it into the ground and it bounces back onto the sticks. Fortunately the bowler sees the lighter side of things, and has a good chuckle
whipped off the legs into deep midwicket
worked out to the covers
drags that short and wide but the batsman can only manage a single, playing that off the back foot down to the man behind point on the boundary
on middle and leg, just short of a good length and that's whisked away in front of square to bring up the inevitable 300
on leg, and that's in the air, just short of the man at deep backward square. McCullum investigates the bottom of his bat, just checking it's still intact
up there, driven back into the ground, but that goes straight and on its way to the boundary, such was the timing. McCullum did well to duck under the ball on its way through
whacked out to deep extra cover
on leg and that's whipped high inside the boundary - "Catch it!" - and indeed Varaiya holds on, dropping forward to take that on his knees. Great take
immediately off the mark with a quick two
reverse swept off the legs and Vettori has to dive at full stretch - and full bat - to get back into his crease
on leg and Vettori gets something, anything, on it, as the ball falls in front and they scramble a quick single
huge strike over mid-on and that's travelling
hit back to the bowler
driven to mid-on
slower ball, short, aerial, and that just beats Collins Obuya at backward point, with an outstretched hand
another slower ball, short again, straight, and the batsman miscues. That's well taken by Tikolo at midwicket, running forward and takes a comfortable catch
wide and that's worked off the back foot behind point
outside off and Vettori tries to leather that but doesn't connect
outside off and that's worked away through extra cover for Vettori's first boundary
short and that's helped on it way off the legs behind square

inn2.comm: Ouma back and across, into line and he blocks it back down the pitch
back once more, pushes into the off side with a call of "wait"
half shout as that nipped back and struck Ouma on the pads, too high and a big inside edge
wide of off stump at 83mph, the first delivery Ouma didn't have to play at
short, Ouma shapes to pull but mistimes the shot and it bobbles up to mid-on at snail's pace

short, and again Ouma goes for the pull, this time he connects but not particularly well and the ball squirts out to square leg. There could have been a run-out there as Obuya was dawdling getting back to the non-striker's end and McCullum spotted that and just missed with his throw
oh yes ... super start at 84mph and a snorting inswinger which cut through Obuya. Had it started a fraction closer to off stump then that would have cleaned Obuya up
no swing, it started outside off and kept going
Obuya up on his toes, all over it as he runs the ball to third man
well left, another one which zipped back off the seam and over the stumps (85.9mph)
another inswinger but one which was heading down the leg, clipped the pads on the way through and McCullum collected the bobbling ball
Ouma back, standing on tip toe, to defend
another at 85.9mph, started outside off and Ouma did not need to play at it
Obuya well forward, pushes the ball to point
Obuya had to play at that as it was on target
straight half volley, hits Obuya on the pads as he shuffled in his crease - he didn't get that far forward - and Rudi Koertzen's finger eventually starts its slow journey towards the heavens
Shah forward and steered to third man
Ouma back, upright, to block
short, Ouma tries a hook but misses and ends up pivoting rather balleticly on his heels
Shah back into line, which is just as well as Bond gets one to jag back at him
wide outside off stump at 88.5mph, Shah fences with little foot movement and misses
short of a length, Shah back and uses the pace of the ball to steer it wide of point
wide and left, bat raises high above the head
half volley driven past extra cover, yet again Ouma doesn't time it. He's not finding the meat of the bat
Shah forced to hurriedly block one that zipped back off a length
Ouma rather rushed by a straight one
back, into line, pushed up to mid-off
Ouma half forward, a loud appeal from Mason who thought the ball hit pad before bat
a peach, Ouma turned square and beaten all ends up
unconvincing backfoot slash uppishly through third or fourth slip
full and on off stump, Shah behind it and blocks into the covers
Bond on the spot, Ouma can do no more than dig it out

Ouma on his toes, prodded into the covers, he called for a run but it seemed to be in slow motion. He was slow to set off, seemed unbothered during the run, despite Vincent bearing down on the ball, and the underarm throw found him two feet short. The third umpire was called for but Ouma wasn't hanging around ...
ripping bouncer at 84mph, Shah jerks his head back out of the way just in time. Bond follows through and gives a hard stare - no words, but no words needed
outside off stump and Shah shoulders arms
slower ball - 77mph - outside off stump and Shah drives at air
too wide, allowing Shah to leave it
Mason finds the spot, Tikolo into line
steered to backward point

hang your head in shame, Steve Tikolo, and offer up a prayer. He clipped the ball to point, it was well picked up and as Tikolo ambled to the non-striker's end, Oram's throw shattered the stumps. He made it but by an inch and more by luck than any judgment. He took his eye off the ball and was oblivious to what was happening
Shah beaten by pace
er ... not sure what's happening here. Pushed into the covers,a quick run considered and declined,  and Vincent's throw would have had Tikolo run-out by about three yards had it hit
loud and confident leg-before shout, Shah saved as it got an inside edge
Tikolo back on his heels and jabs down, not at all assuredly
back and prodded, albeit with a flourish, to cover
short, Tikolo shapes to hook but the ball is on him quicker than he thought and he barely gets a bat onto it and it trickles into the leg side
pushed slightly to leg, a moment's hesitation, Bond across to gather the ball quickly

that's why Tikolo is so highly rated ...he stood tall and drove that off the back foot, it teased Vettori all the way to the rope, although you suspect that in a closer match he would have thrown himself to save the four
good response, beats Tikolo outside the off stump with a slower ball which doesn't carry to McCullum
an ever better shot from Shah. Short, he waited and caressed that off the back foot between cover and extra cover
leggish, pushed towards mid-on
dug in, but too much so and the umpire is displeased. Shah got under that, although he need not have done more than duck rather than go down on his haunches
as short, it climbed on Shah and McCullum was unable to gather it cleanly despite leaping high. It would have been a wide as well, had it not been a no-ball
good length, a big stride forward and defended
Shah into line, pushed to cover and both batsmen yell "wait"
airy-fairy drive, well beaten
Shah again behind that to block
driven off the back foot to point, minimal footwork and a bit of a swish
Tikolo stands tall, again with limited footwork, and drives into the covers
wristily steered to third man, right over the ball and placed
nice ball, angles across Shah
angled again, but too wide and Shah shoulders arms
short, pulled through midwicket, but once more not timed, and the batsmen thought about a third but, given what's happened with their running so far, they opted for discretion
worked into the covers and a quick Vincent throw at the stumps and Tikolo would have been well short - two metres
on off and worked into the covers - another lightning shy, this time from Vettori - all sorts of confusion going on
easy single, at last, and that's dibbled into the covers
attempted yorker, dug out, and that's squeezed into the leg side

short ball, on to him too quickly and that's skied to mid-off and Vettori hangs on for the simplest chance. Two victims now for Mason and that's the big wicket - not that Kenya ever had a realistic hope of chasing down this target, anyway
wobbles that one in on a good length and defended into the leg side
punch-driven through the covers off the back foot, standing tall, and that was a good shot, piercing the field
pushed on to the back foot for a defensive shot that's quiet as you like
short, across the righthander and they get the two easily enough in the end
gone! An outside edge goes through and it's too quick for McCullum, but he parries it with his right glove up to Fleming who casually offers one hand to snatch it
in on leg, short, and Obuya tries to pull that extravagantly, with a touch of the charge, too. Franklin smiles at the audacity of it all
bit more respectful this time and that's played off the back foot into the covers
angled in on off stump and that's defended forward into the covers
on leg this time, but a tidy length, and that's worked into the leg
on leg again and that's worked out inside the midwicket boundary
ran down to third man
in the air, driven well over mid-off and Vettori takes the honours inside the boundary
goes big! Down the track and launches that over long-off but stops on the damp surface and it's easily hunted down
short and swept right over that to work it to leg
on off and that's sneaked into the covers, the batsman getting right over that one
plenty of loop and the batsman comes forward to meet that and drive it into the covers
swept up and there's a fumble on the boundary, but stopped well inside the rope
drags that down and it's defended
Styris the thrower from leg and nearly gets the man at the non-striker's end
short on off and that rises on its way past the batsman's helmet who makes a game effort in hooking that one
short outside off and the batsman chops that one into the ground on its way to point
outside off on a good length and the batsman starts fishing
in the air and Styris fields that one again on the leg side, he's looked sharp in the field today
lovely shot - cracking straight drive of a six over mid-off and Shah just caressed that one. Lovely timing, didn't try to hit that one too hard
dabbed to gully
on off and the batsman creeps forward to defend that strongly
swept round to square easily enough
driven out easily off the front foot to inside the cover boundary
looped in, there's a half shout of Howzat, they got to the "Howz" bit, but it's going down leg
Obuya flummoxed there, expecting the ball to come in much more than it did and it beat him on the way through to the keeper outside off
played easily into the leg side
dribbled out for a quick single
short and hooked up inside the midwicket boundary
clever shot, there, waiting and steering that deliberately just to the keeper's right with a very late, very fine dink through third man
comes forward and drives that one to point
worked out to the square leg boundary
done on length there, the batsman jumping into that one which pops over his outside edge
angles in at the righthander, who works it back out to cover
on a good length, the batsman comes down the track and drives that back to the bowler along the ground, without much power
cuts that off the back foot - doing well to make room - and that goes to point
swept in front of square this time
ooh, arm ball nearly gets the man, a quicker delivery and Shah is tucked up, managing to get an inside edge which chops down past the leg stick
a touch of width, goes for the cut but chops that into the ground again and the ball rolls forward
driven back to the bowler and that's "Good bowling, Dan"
trapped in his crease, slower ball, and swishes a cut over that one
drags that one down and it's driven into the covers for a quick single
squared up trying to turn that one to the leg side
ducks a bouncer
fuller length delivery on the middle and leg, Shah comes on the front foot and drives it to long-on
good length delivery on the off, Shah comes on the front foot to defend
swept behind square, Vettori bowling very wide of the crease here
half an appeal from the Kiwis for one which came up off the boot to first slip - was there a slivery of an edge there?
defended forward
glanced very fine indeed to fine leg
over-stepped no-ball and that's worked into the leg side
looped on to leg and that's worked off the legs to square
way over the line
pops up off the pads and that's a legitimate match now - good job for the Kiwis, really, as the rain's lashing down now
quick single, squeezed out off the back foot into the covers
outside off, a touch short and that's easily worked out inside the cover boundary

spears that one in on off and that's worked to leg. Another terrible mix-up, very poor, and Obuya has been run out. Franklin, throwing in from the boundary, looks up to see both batsmen stranded at the striker's end and he has time to change his mind about where to throw it and Oram takes the bails off. There's no need for the third umpire, there's no need even for the first umpire
thick outside edge past first slip and that will hurry away for four
much better shot, driven beautifully for back-to-back boundaries
left alone outside off, that one arcing away nicely in front of the batsman
angled across the batsman, good ball to start a second spell
again speared across the right hander, too wide though
Odoyo square on and defends
big shout for leg-before, was cleaning him up but pitched outside the line of leg stump, so Billy Doctrove spot on with his dismissive shake of the head
too wide, left alone, nothing doing
outside off stump and Odoyo not to be lured into something rash
short, over Shah's shoulder and a no-ball as well
a little too much width and a controlled steer to third man
slanted down the leg side, off the pads and an easy leg bye
wide and left
a swish and a run as the ball bumbles into the leg side. New Zealand are happy to let Kenya take those all day
checked drive to cover
pushed off the back foot into the off side

dropped leaden footed, a thick edge low to the left of Fleming at first slip and he didn't seem to see it. His exact words were "I didn't ******* see it." Jenny yelled "you plank". I am beginning to suspect she wants an early finish
driven through the covers to add salt to Franklin's wound
played to backward point
full, driven so straight it almost hits the stumps at the other end, but no pace so nothing doing
backfoot drive to extra cover

clipped off his pads to bring up his 12th ODI fifty. He has played some lovely shots - such as that one - but it's been a real curate's egg of an innings. He looks out of sorts but full credit for his battling
short, pulled all along the ground to long leg
full on off stump, driven without any flourish into the off side
pushed out into the covers
super backfoot punch high over mid-on, two bounces over the rope. It was the kind of stroke Tikolo perished to as it got too big on him, but Shah hit that one well
crisp drive to extra cover
wafted over midwicket, high but safe, and McMillan runs round to save the four with a quite unnecessary dive
into the off, no urgency despite a run-rate fast approaching the inflation rate in Zimbabwe
more dots, Odoyo out for some batting practice
well bowled, decent line and length and again played defensively
shortish outside off stump, a swing and a miss from Odoyo
slightly short outside off, well hit off the back foot but right to cover
Odoyo back and fends the ball to mid-on
Shah gives Oram the charge, misses, and the ball hits him in the stomach
outside off, Shah looks to cut and somehow gets the ball to finish up bobbling away to leg behind him. Neat trick
almost a good yorker, a foot too full, and clipped wide of mid-on
Oram gets one to seam back and beats a half-hearted prod
well-placed push to the right of a diving point, he half stops it but cannot save the single
pushed into space, Shah keeps the strike
cracked off the back foot to cover
Shah back, into line, and pushes the ball to mid-off
another dot ball ... the rate will be above 10 an over by the end of this one
slightly airy slash to point
full and hit on the up over mid-on, well connected and it deserved four but it plugged in the soft turf
Shah works into the leg side as the rain gets heavier
good ball, no run, it's getting soggy
Shah pushes into the off side
defensive push
Shah aims a backfoot drive, head in the air, and he misses
driven and a quick single to mid-off. The fielder looked very disinclined to move too quickly for that for fear of slipping
Odoyo takes two steps and smacks Oram back past him, with interest, and the ball rockets to the rope. Great shot ... too late, but a great shot nevertheless
Shah forward to kill the spin
loud shriek from McCullum for leg-before, bat and pad together and nothing doing
Shah again struck on the front foot, that was a really good shout and Doctrove had to think about that
blocked, this time with bat and no alarms
that one slipped, a waist-high full toss and Shah seizes on to and launches it high into the stands over midwicket

half volley, driven hard to Vettori's right and he was down quickly to hold an excellent low catch. There was a moment of uncertainty, but he leapt to his feet and threw the ball jubilantly in the air.
firm push to point
crisp drive on the on side, mid-on round to field
chopped to point who drops to his knees to field
well-timed push off the back foot, it seemed no more than a jab but the ball raced between mid-off and extra cover and was only caught a foot inside the rope
forward, bat and pad together, the ball squirts to point and they stroll a single to get Kamande off the mark
whipped to leg, Odoyo seemed to think that was past midwicket and had to hurry back when the throw came rocketing back
Full and Kamande jabs down on it quite late
Kamande, rather off balance, drives to mid-on
exaggerated lunge to block
Kamande chips the ball over straight midwicket, the ball bouncing between the fielder and long-on. Quite safe
Odoyo forward, circumspect defence
driven pretty weakly to mid-off
good line to start, on off stump and blocked
banged in short, Kamande into line and swings the ball without any venom towards the square-leg boundary
too full, driven through backward point, well timed but the wet grass slows the ball down enough for the man in the deep to catch it
super shot, hit on the up to the left of a diving short mid-on, once it was past him it was four all the way
Mason hits back with a slower ball, past Odoyo and it bounces in front of McCullum and hits him in the ribs. Mason finds that quite funny , McCullum grimaces
driven up and over Mason, not timed as well as the shot early in the over, and they have to settle for the two
a big step to launch it over the top, and then he corrects and runs the ball to backward point
arm ball, neatly run through the slips
a sweep come ungainly heave, no power but a run nevertheless
bobbles into no-man's land
immaculate forward defensive. Just what the situation demands
good for you. Kamande takes a big stride and launches that high over long-on, rows back to the delight of the remaining spectators
after the storm, the lull
lunge, connect and point in quickly
punched off the back foot
turned to straight midwicket
prodded back to the bowler
finally the gap is found, straight and up to long-on
too full and wide, creamed to extra cover. That'll sting but a good stop
blocked, McCullum groans for no apparent reason
pushed to long-on
Kamande steps back aiming to belt that ball out of the ground, sadly for him it was straight and he was fooled by a slightly slower ball and he was through the shot as it thunked into the stumps
flowery off drive to mid-off
full and the batsman jabs down quite late but very effectively
loud and confident appeal for leg-before, to Vettori it was a formality but Billy Doctrove spotted the tiny edge onto pad
squeezes past off stump and McCullum whips off the bails
defensive push
flicked to midwicket
blocked, McCullum stays warm by appealing for something
full, mistimed drive
edged drive, wide third man scuttles round to field
airy drive which Odoyo misses, good ball
up in the blockhole again, dug out
after two attempts, Odoyo middles one and launches it high over the long-on boundary. He gave himself room, followed through and that just went and went
flicked into the off side, well placed
Vettori falls to his right to field a weak drive
Another loud appeal for leg-before from Vettori - not backed by anyone else - and he turns to Billy Doctrove as if done a great wrong
a swing and a miss
opens the face and drives behind point
paddled to long-on
decent yorker, well dug out
McMillan gets excited with a leg-before appeal, again not backed by anyone else
good line, full and dug out
Onyango drives and misses ... "Oh yes," chirps McCullum
pushed to off.  "Oh yes, Danny" chirps McCullum for variety
beaten outside off
an attempted cut, yet again missed
flicked with maximum wristwork to mid-on
very correct defence, lovely textbook stuff
straight and that's dabbed down off the back foot
on leg and that's worked in front of midwicket for a quick single
oh, that one swung in late and cut him in half - not literally, he may be a bowling wizard but he's not a magician
crashed in on leg and there's a half-shout which they pull out of, but it's too quick for the batsman
fast, straight yorker dug out well
wide outside off, a well-disguised slower ball and the batsman gamely swishes at that in a bid to improve the Net Run Rate, alas, no, he misses
worked down off the back foot behind point
on the off stump, a good length, and that's worked to mid-on
driven straight to mid-on
worked out into the covers
defended this time

comes from vaguely wide of the wicket and angles that right in at the righthander, who squeezes it into the covers. Brilliant piece of fielding by Vincent, nimble, and underarmed that one in at the stumps. The third umpire needed just the one replay for that. Vincent like a hawk, there
short and that's smashed in front of midwicket - four all the way
slower ball inside edged to square
testing delivery, jinking past the outside edge
short ball, ducked
on leg, bouncer, but not as much lift as the batsman was expecting and he crouches into it, the ball crashing into his ribs
oh, how did that miss? Full delivery, edged into the ground, just past the sticks and McCullum's shaking his right hand in pain after taking that one awkwardly
driven slowly to long-on
short and dibbled off the back foot down behind point
flicked off the legs in front of midwicket
nips at the righthander off the seam, but still with width outside the off stump and that's late cut behind point
nips in at the righthander who bends over to defend
on leg and the batsman tries to drive to cover
deceived by the slower ball but does well to adjust and play that up aerially through cover with a square drive, a bit more luck than skill, it's true, but it was timed away well all the same
goes to straight drive that one aerially and that's sliced up in the air to point where Oram makes no mistake
pushed right up there and that's defended forward
defended this time
nearly got bat on that one, jumping at the one which curves away
defended forward
defended forward
play and a miss
worked off the toes square and that's a quick single
poked off the toes into the short midwicket region
leans over that one and that's worked to square
angled in to the righthander and that's defended forward
driven forward to mid-off
angled into the righthander, short, and that nearly hits him on the shoulder
defended forward
short, straight and that's defended down off the back foot
tries a yorker, overpitches and that's a low full toss; still, they can be tricky to play and that's driven out to cover
oh, nearly undone by the slower ball, just prodding at that one as it steeples past the outside edge
round the wicket and that's left alone outside off
round the wicket again, a decent line, and that swings ever so slightly away from the righthander
on leg and that's worked off the back foot into the covers
wings that one in at the righthander and that was driven into the covers
on middle and that's again driven out to cover and it's winged back in
slower ball, tricksy one, and the batsman plays over that one, nearly getting the edge, there
on off, a touch short, and that's worked off the back foot into the covers
slashes outside the off stump and nearly gets an edge on it again
driven slowly into the on side
on off and that's worked off the back foot into the covers
on off and that's worked into the leg side
short and that one rises on its way past the batsman's nose, he arcs gently away from it
short ball, attempts a bouncer, the batsman ducks into that and it crashes into the helmet, as it doesn't get up as much as he was expecting
and the match comes to an end with Franklin throwing in a consecutive bouncer which the batsman tries to hook and gets only an edge which pops up and is pouched tidily
